Nigerians will pay more for electricity as the review of electricity tariff by the Nigerian Electricity Regulatory Commission (NERC) comes into effect this year. The upward review of the tariff which was approved by the regulatory commission in December 2019 will however be suspended for customers of the 11 distribution companies (DisCos) until April 2020. This was disclosed in the December publication of NERC’s 2019 Minor Review of the Multi Year Tariff Order (MYTO) 2015 and the Minimum Remittance Order (MRO) for 2020. According to the publication, the commission gave the caveat on the frozen tariff hike thus: “The federal government’s updated Power Sector Recovery Programme (PSPRP) does not envisage an immediate increase in end-users tariffs until 1st April 2020 and a transition to full cost reflectivity by end of 2021.” To bridge the funding gap since customers will not pay the new tariff till April, NERC in the publication dated December 31, 2019 and signed by the NERC chairman, Prof. James Momoh and the commissioner for Legal, Licencing and Compliance, Dafe Akpeneye, noted: “In the interim, the federal government is committed to fund the revenue gap between the cost reflective tariff and the actual tariff NERC allows customers to pay.” NERC said the review considered changes in macroeconomic indices like inflation at 11.3 percent, exchange rate at N309.9 to a dollar, and gas price at $3.30 per standard cubic feet (scuf). According to orders obtained for the 11 DisCos which varies across the distribution companies, LEADERSHIP Sunday learnt that Abuja DisCo customers, for instance, ought to pay an average of N54.3 per kilowatt hour (KWH) as cost reflective tariff effective from January 1, 2020. However, NERC said it should continue collecting N32.7. Hence, Residential 2 (R2) customers’ bill remains at N24.30/kwh till April when the PRSP stipulates a hike. But it must remit 42 percent as payment for monthly bulk energy to the Nigerian Bulk Electricity Trading Plc (NBET). In Lagos, Ikeja DisCo customers who ought to pay N44.6/kwh would be allowed to pay N27.3/kwh in the interim. While its Residential customers continue to pay N21.30/kwh, the DisCo is expected to remit 49 percent bulk energy payment. For Eko DisCo, customers will pay N28.3/kwh on average instead of N47.0/kwh cost reflective amount. Residential customers will continue to pay N24/kwh but must remit 43 percent bulk energy settlement to NBET. For Kano DisCo, customers will pay N52.7/kwh on average. They are allowed to pay N30.1/kwh. The DisCo which collects N22.50/kwh from Residential customers now, must pay 38 percent of its monthly bulk energy bill. The Enugu DisCo averagely collects N35.3/kwh from customers instead of N54.4/kwh. Residential customers pay N30.93/kwh while the DisCo must pay 42 percent monthly bulk energy invoice to NBET. In July last year, NERC approved five retroactive minor electricity tariff reviews of the Multi-Year Tariff Order (MYTO) 2015 that were left undone since June, 2016 to cover for the last half of 2016 up to the end of 2018. This excluded the first half of 2019 and Minimum Remittance Order (MRO) for the distribution companies (DisCos). MYTO 2015 was implemented on February 1, 2016 and was to be renewed every six months but were never approved for the DisCos to implement-situation the DisCos saw as a breach of agreement and unproductive, while the authorities felt it was unwarranted in the face of the poor service being provided, such as the epileptic and ineffective power supply to customers. The information released by NERC also envisaged another review that would come into effect on January 1, 2020. Confirming the tariff hike to LEADERSHIP Sunday on the eve of new year, NERC chairman, Prof. James Momoh said the review would go on as proposed. “It will happen”, he said. NERC proposed in the Order an intermediate review of end-user tariffs on January 1, 2020 while transition to full cost reflective tariff is to be achieved by July 2020. The Minor review was undertaken pursuant to Section 17 of the MYTO – 2015 Order which provides for a biannual minor review of tariffs taking into consideration changes in variables outside the control of the DisCos in line with the requirements of the MYTO Methodology, i.e. Inflation rates, Foreign Exchange rates, Gas prices and Available generation capacity.